## Appendix A: Distinguishing between XX and XY Hamiltonian (2 ions) 

If we start with the Hamiltonian \(H=J^{x}_{12}\sigma_{x}^{1}\sigma_{x}^{2}+J^{y}_{12}\sigma_{y}^{1}\sigma_{y}^{2}\)and the evolution operator U such that \(U(\tau)=\mathrm{exp}(-iH\tau)\). It is easy to show that: 


*  U \(\ket{\downarrow\downarrow}\)= \(\cos{\left(\tau\left(J^{x}_{12}-J^{y}_{12}\right)\right)}\)\(\ket{\downarrow\downarrow}\)\(i\sin{\left(\tau\left(J^{x}_{12}-J^{y}_{12}\right)\right)}\)\(\ket{\uparrow\uparrow}\)
*  U \(\ket{\uparrow\uparrow}\)= \(\cos{\left(\tau\left(J^{x}_{12}-J^{y}_{12}\right)\right)}\)\(\ket{\uparrow\uparrow}\)\(i\sin{\left(\tau\left(J^{x}_{12}-J^{y}_{12}\right)\right)}\)\(\ket{\downarrow\downarrow}\)
*  U \(\ket{\downarrow\uparrow}\)= \(\cos{\left(\tau\left(J^{x}_{12}+J^{y}_{12}\right)\right)}\)\(\ket{\downarrow\uparrow}\)\(i\sin{\left(\tau\left(J^{x}_{12}+J^{y}_{12}\right)\right)}\)\(\ket{\uparrow\downarrow}\)
*  U \(\ket{\uparrow\downarrow}\)= \(\cos{\left(\tau\left(J^{x}_{12}+J^{y}_{12}\right)\right)}\)\(\ket{\uparrow\downarrow}\)\(i\sin{\left(\tau\left(J^{x}_{12}+J^{y}_{12}\right)\right)}\)\(\ket{\downarrow\uparrow}\)

For the case of the XY Hamiltonian, we have that \(J^{x}_{12}=J^{y}_{12}\). When initialized in \(\ket{\downarrow\downarrow}\), we do not expect to see oscillations between ( \(\ket{\downarrow\downarrow}\), \(\ket{\uparrow\uparrow}\)). But when initialized in \(\ket{\downarrow\uparrow}\), we expect to see oscillations between ( \(\ket{\downarrow\uparrow}\), \(\ket{\uparrow\downarrow}\)) at a frequency of ( \(J^{x}_{12}+J^{y}_{12}\)). 

